Within the compressor of a modern turbofan engine, the stagnation temperature and stagnation pressure within the main gas path are found to be \({\color[rgb]{0.164799,0.878862,0.723179}500 \; K}\) and \({\color[rgb]{0.315209,0.728565,0.037706}13 \; atmospheres}\). The static pressure here is measured to be \({\color[rgb]{0.315209,0.728565,0.037706}10 \; atmospheres}\). What is the velocity of the gas? You may assume the heat capacity ratio, \(\gamma=1.4\) and a specific gas constant value of \(R=287 \; J/(K \cdot kg)\). Hint: Assume the flow is isentropic. \({\color[rgb]{0.028509,0.250925,0.501969}[8]}\)
{
The solution to this problem can be obtained either via the tables or via a direct calculation. First, note that the relationship between the static and stagnation pressures permits us to work out the Mach number, i.e.,
\[\begin{equation*}
\begin{split}
\frac{p_{0}}{p} & = \left( 1 + \frac{\left( \gamma - 1 \right)}{2} M^2 \right)^{\frac{\gamma}{\gamma - 1}} \\
\frac{13}{10} & = \left( 1 + \frac{\left( 0.4 \right)}{2} M^2 \right)^{\frac{1.4}{0.4}}
\end{split}
\end{equation*}\]
which leads to \(M = 0.624\). To work out the velocity, we need to determine the speed of sound, \(a = \sqrt{\gamma R T}\) where \(T\) is the static temperature (this step is very important–using the stagnation temperature here is wrong!). Using the isentropic flow relations, we have
\[\begin{equation*}
\begin{split}
\frac{p_0}{p} = \frac{13}{10}  & = \left( \frac{T_0}{T} \right)^{\gamma / (\gamma - 1 )} \\
& = \left( \frac{500}{T} \right)^{1.4 / 0.4}
\end{split}
\end{equation*}\]
which implies that \(T=463.89 \; K\). This yields \(a = \sqrt{1.4 \times 287 \times 463.89} = 431.73 \; m/s\). The velocity is then given by \(v = M a = 0.624 \times 431.73 = 269.4 \; m/s\). }

